WEBVTT

00:00:00.120 --> 00:00:05.330
Let’s explore the interpolation feature, a central component of PyAnalySeries

00:00:05.860 --> 00:00:09.990
Thanks to the application’s interactivity, defining an interpolation becomes a

00:00:09.990 --> 00:00:12.460
simple and intuitive process!

00:00:12.460 --> 00:00:14.870
Let’s consider a real use case.

00:00:14.870 --> 00:00:17.660
The files are available in the installation directory.

00:00:17.660 --> 00:00:20.080
First, open the files.

00:00:20.080 --> 00:00:23.520
You can load multiple files, referred to as WorkSheets in

00:00:23.520 --> 00:00:24.930
the application.

00:00:24.930 --> 00:00:27.420
The file format is based on the open.

00:00:27.420 --> 00:00:29.790
xlsx spreadsheet standard.

00:00:29.790 --> 00:00:32.770
Open the two files as shown in the video.

00:00:32.770 --> 00:00:36.990
Select the variables to interpolate and the corresponding reference series

00:00:36.990 --> 00:00:41.390
for delta C 13 and delta O 18.

00:00:41.390 --> 00:00:43.830
Use the Control key to add multiple series to your

00:00:43.830 --> 00:00:45.100
selection.

00:00:45.100 --> 00:00:49.310
The selection order does not matter, although for simplicity we

00:00:49.310 --> 00:00:51.890
will choose the reference series first.

00:00:51.890 --> 00:00:55.210
Now open the window used to define an interpolation.

00:00:55.210 --> 00:01:00.490
In practice, this consists of identifying correspondences between two series

00:01:01.160 --> 00:01:04.790
This is where interactivity becomes essential, as it allows you

00:01:04.790 --> 00:01:09.190
to place tie points either on transitions or precisely on

00:01:09.190 --> 00:01:10.680
individual points.

00:01:10.680 --> 00:01:13.450
We now have four series selected.

00:01:13.450 --> 00:01:17.660
Start with delta O 18, and specify the reference series

00:01:17.690 --> 00:01:20.910
and the series to be interpolated using the selection controls

00:01:21.650 --> 00:01:24.330
Identify similar transition zones.

00:01:26.520 --> 00:01:29.680
Using the Shift key, click to place a vertical dashed

00:01:29.680 --> 00:01:33.620
line at each corresponding transition in both windows.

00:01:33.620 --> 00:01:36.040
Then connect the two lines by pressing the C key

00:01:37.440 --> 00:01:40.980
This creates a pair of corresponding points, referred to as

00:01:40.980 --> 00:01:42.270
pointers.

00:01:42.270 --> 00:01:44.090
Select another transition.

00:01:46.260 --> 00:01:50.040
Once two pairs of pointers have been defined, the interpolation

00:01:50.040 --> 00:01:52.030
is automatically displayed.

00:01:52.030 --> 00:01:55.400
Press Z or enable the “ Show interpolated curve ”

00:01:55.400 --> 00:01:58.050
checkbox to toggle its visibility.

00:01:58.050 --> 00:02:01.270
You can also visualize the effect of the interpolation method

00:02:01.590 --> 00:02:03.820
whether linear or polynomial.

00:02:03.820 --> 00:02:07.750
Continue this iterative process by placing a pointer directly on

00:02:07.750 --> 00:02:08.960
a data point.

00:02:08.960 --> 00:02:11.730
To do this, hold the Control key and click on

00:02:11.730 --> 00:02:12.510
the point.

00:02:12.790 --> 00:02:16.200
Repeat the same operation on the reference series and connect

00:02:16.200 --> 00:02:17.270
the two pointers.

00:02:19.440 --> 00:02:22.440
To summarize: use the Shift key to place a pointer

00:02:22.440 --> 00:02:25.220
freely, or the Control key to snap it to a

00:02:25.220 --> 00:02:26.440
data point.

00:02:26.440 --> 00:02:28.860
You can undo the last connection by clicking the “

00:02:28.860 --> 00:02:32.060
Remove last connection ” button or by pressing the U

00:02:32.060 --> 00:02:32.860
key.

00:02:32.860 --> 00:02:35.590
You can also remove a connection by hovering over it—it

00:02:36.290 --> 00:02:39.120
will turn red—and then pressing the X key.

00:02:40.390 --> 00:02:44.170
Pressing uppercase X prompts you to remove all pointers.

00:02:45.610 --> 00:02:48.290
You can review the values of the defined pointers at

00:02:48.320 --> 00:02:50.440
any time in the Pointers tab.

00:02:50.440 --> 00:02:53.750
In the Pointers plot tab, you can visualize X2 as

00:02:53.750 --> 00:02:57.270
a function of X1, as well as the corresponding gradient

00:02:57.480 --> 00:03:02.370
If X2 represents time and X1 represents depth, this gradient

00:03:02.370 --> 00:03:04.550
corresponds to the sedimentation rate.

00:03:05.650 --> 00:03:08.740
During the definition of an interpolation, you may need to

00:03:08.740 --> 00:03:11.940
switch to another variable to refine or adjust your pointers

00:03:12.450 --> 00:03:16.390
Switch to delta C 13 by selecting the reference series

00:03:16.420 --> 00:03:18.180
and the series to be interpolated.

00:03:20.490 --> 00:03:24.700
Define a correspondence on a transition and create the connection

00:03:25.340 --> 00:03:28.690
Now switch back to delta O 18.

00:03:31.990 --> 00:03:35.630
This process can be repeated iteratively until the desired result

00:03:35.630 --> 00:03:36.430
is obtained.

00:03:37.590 --> 00:03:40.330
Let’s look at the result produced by an expert user

00:03:44.840 --> 00:03:47.920
Once satisfied with the result, you can save either the

00:03:47.920 --> 00:03:51.020
full interpolation or only the pointers.

00:03:51.020 --> 00:03:54.130
You can also load an existing pointer file and continue

00:03:54.130 --> 00:03:57.070
refining or redefining the pointers.

00:03:57.070 --> 00:03:59.290
In the next step, we will see how to apply

00:03:59.290 --> 00:04:02.200
the defined interpolation to a set of series.
